A CV-screening system used to rank, filter, or reject job applicants is a high-risk AI system under the EU AI Act, specifically Annex III for employment, worker management, and access to self-employment. That classification applies because it materially affects access to work and is explicitly listed when used for recruitment or selection decisions. The key verifiable property to enforce is non-discriminatory performance across protected groups, because unlawful bias is the core high-stakes failure mode in CV screening. In practice, make that property auditable by requiring bounded disparity in outcomes and errors, such as an adverse impact ratio of at least 0.8 and controlled false-negative/false-positive rate gaps across sex, age, ethnicity proxies where lawful, and other protected classes. Also require full logging of inputs, scores, overrides, and reviewer actions so those metrics can be independently reproduced. Human oversight, documentation, and robustness are also mandatory, but the most important enforceable property is measurable fairness with reproducible audit evidence.
